Cell.Data: Specific XDS profile for the general document reference functionality
This maps to the FHIR id

Globally unique identifier assigned to the document by the creating entity. A DocumentEntry representing a single document is identified by the uniqueId attribute; the linkage between DocumentEntry and the Document it represents is made with the uniqueId attribute. This unique identifier may be used in other documents to reference this document
The patientId represents the subject of care of the document. The value of the patientId shall be the same for all new documents of a SubmissionSet
In the context of XDS, the patientId shall be the one with use = official

The code specifying the precise kind of document (e.g., Pulmonary History and Physical, Discharge Summary, Ultrasound Report). It is suggested that the creating entity draw these values from a coding scheme providing a fine level of granularity.
Represents the humans and/or machines that authored the document.

Represents a participant within the authorInstitution who has legally authenticated or attested the document. Legal authentication implies that a document has been signed manually or electronically by the legalAuthenticator
Usually just a name, so use a contained resource - but if an id is provided, may be able to identify it
Represents the time the author created the document

Represents the status of the DocumentEntry. A DocumentEntry shall have one of two availability statuses: Approved available for patient care Deprecated obsolete This attribute is omitted in a submission of new documents. It is always set to Approved as a result of the successful submission of new documents. It may be changed to Deprecated under the primary responsibility of the creating entity If a DocumentEntry is deleted, there is no such state as "the Document Entry is removed" (only an audit trail is kept if such a deletion is allowed)

Approved ==> current, Deprecated ==> superceded.
FHIR requires this to be filled out with "current" in a submission of new documents
The current document is a replacement of the referenced document

Represents the title of the document. Clinical documents often do not have a title, in such case the classCode (e.g., a "consultation" or "progress note") is often used as the title. In that case, the title is usually omitted.

The code specifying the level of confidentiality of the document. These codes are set by policy of the creating entity and issues related to highly sensitive documents are beyond the scope of metadata definition. These issues are expected to be addressed separately. confidentialityCode is part of a codification scheme
Multiple codes != multiple concepts under document reference
Specifies the human language of character data in the document
MIME type of the document in the Repository

Globally unique code specifying the format of the document. Along with the typeCode, it should provide sufficient information to allow potential document consumer to know if it will be able to process the document. The formatCode shall be sufficiently specific to ensure processing/display by identifying a document encoding, structure and template (e.g., for a CDA Document, the fact that it complies with a CDA schema, possibly a template and the choice of a content-specific style sheet).

Format codes may be specified by multiple organizations. Format codes defined by the IHE ITI domain shall have names with the prefix urn:ihe:iti: Format codes defined by other IHE domains shall have names with the prefix urn:ihe:’domain initials’: Format codes defined by the creating entity shall have names with the prefix urn:ad: ’name of creating entity’: Creating Entity shall be unique

Size in bytes of the byte stream that comprises the document. If this attribute is present in a transaction, it might be validated. The rules for validation are specified in the relevant profile. If this attribute is missing, it may be created using the rules in the relevant profile

The hash key of the contents of the document. If this attribute is present in a transaction, it may be validated; the rules for validation are specified in the relevant profile. If this attribute is missing, it may be created using the rules in the relevant profile
The URI element shall point to the file containing the document
Although there is no source mapping, it probably makes a great deal of sense to add a service reference to an XDS.b service call to get this document (useful in a mixed FHIR/XDS eco-system)

This list of codes represents the main clinical acts, such as a colonoscopy or an appendectomy, being documented. In some cases, the event is inherent in the typeCode, such as a "History and Physical Report" in which the procedure being documented is necessarily a "History and Physical" act. An event can further specialize the act inherent in the typeCode, such as where it is simply "Procedure Report" and the procedure was a "colonoscopy". If one or more eventCodes are included, they shall not conflict with the values inherent in the classCode, practiceSettingCode or typeCode, as such a conflict would create an ambiguous situation

Represents the start & stop time of the service being documented took place (clinically significant, but not necessarily when the document was produced or approved). This may be the same as the encounter time in case the service was delivered during an encounter

Note: If needed, other times associated with the document, such as time of approval, are to be recorded, within the document. If the Service happens at a point in time, the starat and stop attributes shall contain the same value as the serviceStartTime

This code represents the type of organizational setting of the clinical encounter during which the documented act occurred. In some cases, the setting of the encounter is inherent in the typeCode, such as "Diabetes Clinic Progress Note". healthcareFacilityTypeCode shall be equivalent to or further specialize the value inherent in the typeCode; for example, where the typeCode is simply "Clinic Progress Note" and the value of healthcareFacilityTypeCode is "private clinic"
Demographics information at the time of submission of the patient to whose medical record this document belongs
Represents the humans and/or machines that authored the document
The document author may be the patient itself
The document author may be the patient itself

Represents the telecommunications address (e.g. email) of the document author
Intended to assist with automated routing of other messages intended for the document author.
Represents a specific healthcare facility under which the human and/or machines authored the document
Organization will have name and maybe id
represents the role of the author with respect to the patient at the time the document was created
Represents a specific specialty within a healthcare facility under which the human and/or machines authored the document

the set of codes specifying the type of clinical activity that resulted in placing Documents in this Folder. These values shall be drawn from a vocabulary or coding scheme defined by the creating entity
The patientId represents the primary subject of care of the Folder

The code specifying the particular kind of document (e.g., Prescription, Discharge Summary, Report).Valid values for this metadata attribute are specified by the policies of the creating entity. It is suggested that the creating entity draws these values from a coding scheme providing a coarse level of granularity (about 10 to 100 entries).
For example, XDS specifies that the XDS Affinity Domain will establish this list
A globally unique identifier for a community
Clinical specialty where the act that resulted in the document was performed

The code specifying the clinical specialty where the act that resulted in the document was performed (e.g., Family Practice, Laboratory, Radiology). It is suggested that the creating entity draws these values from a coding scheme providing a coarse level of granularity (about 10 to 100 entries).
Identifier of the repository where the document is stored

The globally unique, immutable, identifier of the repository where the document is stored, assigned by the Document Repository. This unique identifier for the Document Repository may be used to identify and connect to the specific Document Repository where the document is stored once its metadata has been retrieved from a Document Registry. The repository unique Id is used by various profiles to facilitate the location of services and documents
